===Etymology===
From Anglo-Saxon '''[[abbod]]''', '''[[abbad]]''', from  Latin '''[[abbas]]''', '''[[abbatis]]''', from Greek '''[[&#7936;&beta;&beta;&alpha;&#834;&#962;]]''', from [[Syriac]] '''[[abb&#257;]]''',  ''father''. Cf. [[Abba]], [[Abbé]].

===Noun===
#The superior or head of an [[abbey]].
#One of a class of bishops whose sees were formerly [[abbeys]]. - ''Encyclopaedia Britannica''

[[N.B.]] A female abbot is called an '''[[abbess]]'''.

